            "content_html": "<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Prayer Room Vastu Shastra Tips For A Peaceful Home</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Your prayer room must not only be a sacred space, but it should also exude positive energy that will help you relax and meditate. When the <strong>temple</strong> or <strong>prayer area</strong> is properly constructed as per <strong>Vastu Shastra</strong>, it can provide the home and its inhabitant\u2019s health, wealth, and happiness. While every Indian household has a puja room, have you ever pondered why some give off a positive feeling as soon as you walk in, while others don&#8217;t? The answer might be because only a few individuals are familiar with <strong>Vastu</strong> concepts. To make things easier for you, we&#8217;ve compiled a list of the most significant puja room Vastu guidelines for your home. Continue reading to learn more.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What is the best way to construct a temple at home, as per Vastu?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When erecting the temple, avoid placing it straight on the ground. Well, Nitien Parmar of VastuPlus suggests keeping it on a higher platform or pedestal. Either stonework or timber should be used to construct the temple. Glass or acrylic temples should be avoided. Do not overcrowd the temple. Make sure you don&#8217;t have several idols of the same Deity in the temple, whether they&#8217;re sitting or standing. \u201cIdols or pictures put in the temple should not be broken or torn, as this is regarded as unlucky,\u201d Parmar of VastuPlus advises.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Pujas ought to be performed wherever the temple is located. The entire family usually prays together during festivities. As a result, make sure there is adequate room for the entire family to assemble and pray. The aura in the temple area should be healthy and balanced. So make it tidy and free of dust and insects, and don&#8217;t overcrowd the area with too many embellishments.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What is the right direction to locate your puja room at home?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Your puja room&#8217;s placement is essential in determining its auspicious ambiance. The best direction is north-east, followed by east and north. If you&#8217;re building a new house and have discretion over where your puja room is located, we highly advise you to avoid the basement or upper levels. It&#8217;s ideal if your prayer room is built on the ground level.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">You must be wondering what the logic behind this is. Vastu Shastra promotes the north-east direction to maximize solar energy harvesting. Furthermore, the earth is also tilted towards the northeast direction. As a result, the northeast direction is considered auspicious since it allows the prayer area to draw all of the home&#8217;s energy towards it and then propel it forward. Not only that but it is said that Jupiter is the lord of the same direction. Consequently, this direction is referred to as <strong>Ishan Kona</strong> or Home of Jupiter.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What is the ideal way to design your puja room?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The ceiling in your puja room should be low. A pyramid-shaped upper surface will help to create a peaceful environment. If there is enough room, a threshold and two-door entry must be taken into consideration. According to Vastu Shastra, installing only one door is not recommended. This is due to the fact that a single, outward-opening door might get in the way of the person praying, disrupting their state of mind. If you don&#8217;t have enough space or money to construct a door, simply drape a curtain to function as a temporary doorway.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Since the puja room is compact, the lower ceiling, along with the pyramid-shaped structure offers equilibrium and makes it easier to enter a spiritual experience. The purpose of a threshold is to keep bugs and pests out of sacred areas.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What is the best way to place idols in the temple?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It&#8217;s time to put in your idols once your puja room&#8217;s design and construction are complete. A few inches away from the wall and at least six inches from the floor would be preferable. Deceased people&#8217;s portraits and artworks showing violence have no place in your puja room.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To maintain consistent air movement around the idol, it should be placed away from the wall. This also helps to surround the deity with the scent of the incense sticks.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>How should I store things in the puja room?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Are you unsure about where to put all of your religious literature, candles, and puja items? Storage must always face south-east. Why you may ask? Storage should face south-east to ensure that sunlight is not obstructed. Additionally, there should be no storage above the deity. All storage must be placed under the idols. Disrespect is shown by storing items above idols. It also has an impact on the free movement of energy and light. This is not only helpful in terms of Vastu, but it is also practical because items placed at ground level are easily accessible.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What should be the colour of the puja room?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The colour of the prayer room should be according to the Vastu guidelines. Vastu Shastra recommends subdued colours for maintaining the serenity of a puja area. Whites, soft blues, and pastel yellow are all appropriate colours. In a puja room, gloomy colours should be avoided since these will not create a peaceful atmosphere in a place of worship and can be distracting instead. The majority of temple units in Indian houses, however, are constructed of dark wood. This is a Vastu Dosha that prevents divinity from entering your household. If you already have a dark-colored puja unit that you don&#8217;t want to replace, consider painting the wall behind it with a bright colour. To counteract the gloomy colour, the bright colour offers enough illumination to the unit.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Likewise, for the flooring of your puja area, choose white marble or any light-colored marble tiling.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What should be the lighting of the puja room?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What&#8217;s not to like about a space that&#8217;s bright? And, more importantly, a bright puja room? As it will be the smallest room in your house, it will require bright lighting. With a window facing northeast, light up your prayer area with Diyas. If this isn&#8217;t possible, make do with plenty of artificial lighting.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Not only will your puja room be bright, but you&#8217;ll also have enough air and be able to sit comfortably while praying for lengthy periods of time if you have a north-east facing window.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Have a Small Apartment? Here are some tips for the ideal prayer room.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">People in today&#8217;s world of nuclear families and small flats don&#8217;t have the luxury of devoting an entire room to praying. The trend for compact fully prepared puja mandaps that can be mounted on walls and hallways has increased as a result.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Living Room</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The greatest spot to install a puja unit in a small flat is in the living room. If you have empty shelves in your entertainment unit, you may create a separate puja room by decorating a tiny section. For those who spend long hours in meditation and prayer, however, solitude and focus will continue to be a problem.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Kitchen</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A kitchen cabinet may be customized to function as a miniature temple. It is advised to make the cabinet door have chiseled edges and shapely openings on its surface so that smoke can be properly dispersed when diyas and fragrance sticks are lighted.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Corners</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Placing up a series of elegant pedestals so that the idols are a few inches above the ground level may quickly transform an empty corner of the dining room into a puja space. Small lights can be placed above the idols to brighten the prayer area. If you need seclusion, hang a little curtain beneath the top shelf to keep the idols hidden from view.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Cupboards</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Why not construct a closet for the deities with sophisticated customizable doors and shelves while constructing a cupboard for everyday use goods at home? This can be the ultimate space-saving puja area for a tiny flat. For further decoration, you can add brass fittings on the cabinet sides and broad shelves with roomy drawers at the bottom.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Designing a temple at home: what to do and what not to do</strong></p>\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n<li>To maintain the sacredness of the holy place, the puja room should always be separated by doors. As per Vastu, a puja space without a door is inauspicious. This is because the pious spirits inside a puja room might wane if there isn&#8217;t a door.</li>\n<li>A Diya, lamp, or anything else you light in the puja space as per religion must be lit on the right-hand side of the person offering prayers.</li>\n<li>Maintain a clutter-free and spotless puja space.</li>\n<li>Ensure that an electric switchboard is located near the temple so that the area may be lit up during festive occasions.</li>\n<li>When worshiping in the puja room, idols and pictures of God must never face each other; deities facing north or east are regarded as auspicious.</li>\n<li>The shrine should be built high enough for the statues&#8217; feet to be at the level of the chest of the person who is worshiping. Never put the god statue down on the ground.</li>\n<li>A temple or puja area cannot be built against a wall with a bathroom behind it. The justification for not placing the sacred space next to the restroom is to prevent bad energy from entering the house.</li>\n<li>Bold or dark hues, such as black, gray, or any other gloomy hue, should never be used in the prayer area.</li>\n<li>Avoid putting trash cans in the puja area since this raises the chances of bad energy flowing through the atmosphere.</li>\n<li>Remove any wilted flowers from the puja space. As soon as the flowers and foliage lose their freshness, remove them from this area.</li>\n<li>It is deemed inauspicious to place the puja area under a stairway or against the toilet wall. It is considered a big Vastu dosha.</li>\n<li>When storing water, make use of copper vessels rather than glass or low-cost metals such as aluminium.</li>\n<li>To get the greatest benefits, place the puja ghar on the bottom level of your house. According to Vastu, mandirs should not be built in basements or on upper levels.</li>\n<li>According to Vastu Shastra, you should not have a temple in your bedroom. If you absolutely have to place it in the bedroom, make sure your feet aren&#8217;t facing the temple.</li>\n</ol>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>FAQs</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Where in the house should the puja area be located?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Building a puja room should be done in the northeast, east, or north orientations. These directions are said to be the luckiest. To guarantee that the puja rooms are free of bad energy, keep them away from the stairwells and restrooms.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Which sort of mandir is suitable for use at home?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A mandir built of wood, as per Vastu Shastra, is auspicious and regarded more holy. Apart from other wood kinds, Sheesham Wood (Rosewood) is deemed blessed for temples.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Which metal is considered propitious for puja?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is recommended to utilize objects made of clay, silver, copper, or gold in a puja. Favorable energies are easily received by these things. Owing to the high cost of silver and gold, it may be more cost-effective to use copper, brass, or stone items.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Which items should be avoided in the puja room?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Leather is regarded as an impure material to keep in the mandir. The temple space must not contain any animal skin. Also, don&#8217;t store cash in the puja room. While it is not deemed unclean, saving/storing money at a place where you seek serenity and prosperity is not deemed appropriate.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What Colour scheme should you choose in your puja room? </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Choose pastel colours such as white, blue and yellow. These emit a sense of calm and tranquilly that is conducive to prayer.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/prayer-room-vastu-shastra-tips-for-a-peaceful-home\">Prayer Room Vastu Shastra Tips For A Peaceful Home</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog\">Real Estate News</a>.</p>\n",
            "content_text": "Prayer Room Vastu Shastra Tips For A Peaceful Home\nYour prayer room must not only be a sacred space, but it should also exude positive energy that will help you relax and meditate. When the temple or prayer area is properly constructed as per Vastu Shastra, it can provide the home and its inhabitant\u2019s health, wealth, and happiness. While every Indian household has a puja room, have you ever pondered why some give off a positive feeling as soon as you walk in, while others don&#8217;t? The answer might be because only a few individuals are familiar with Vastu concepts. To make things easier for you, we&#8217;ve compiled a list of the most significant puja room Vastu guidelines for your home. Continue reading to learn more.\nWhat is the best way to construct a temple at home, as per Vastu?\nWhen erecting the temple, avoid placing it straight on the ground. Well, Nitien Parmar of VastuPlus suggests keeping it on a higher platform or pedestal. Either stonework or timber should be used to construct the temple. Glass or acrylic temples should be avoided. Do not overcrowd the temple. Make sure you don&#8217;t have several idols of the same Deity in the temple, whether they&#8217;re sitting or standing. \u201cIdols or pictures put in the temple should not be broken or torn, as this is regarded as unlucky,\u201d Parmar of VastuPlus advises.\nPujas ought to be performed wherever the temple is located. The entire family usually prays together during festivities. As a result, make sure there is adequate room for the entire family to assemble and pray. The aura in the temple area should be healthy and balanced. So make it tidy and free of dust and insects, and don&#8217;t overcrowd the area with too many embellishments.\nWhat is the right direction to locate your puja room at home?\nYour puja room&#8217;s placement is essential in determining its auspicious ambiance. The best direction is north-east, followed by east and north. If you&#8217;re building a new house and have discretion over where your puja room is located, we highly advise you to avoid the basement or upper levels. It&#8217;s ideal if your prayer room is built on the ground level.\nYou must be wondering what the logic behind this is. Vastu Shastra promotes the north-east direction to maximize solar energy harvesting. Furthermore, the earth is also tilted towards the northeast direction. As a result, the northeast direction is considered auspicious since it allows the prayer area to draw all of the home&#8217;s energy towards it and then propel it forward. Not only that but it is said that Jupiter is the lord of the same direction. Consequently, this direction is referred to as Ishan Kona or Home of Jupiter.\nWhat is the ideal way to design your puja room?\nThe ceiling in your puja room should be low. A pyramid-shaped upper surface will help to create a peaceful environment. If there is enough room, a threshold and two-door entry must be taken into consideration. According to Vastu Shastra, installing only one door is not recommended. This is due to the fact that a single, outward-opening door might get in the way of the person praying, disrupting their state of mind. If you don&#8217;t have enough space or money to construct a door, simply drape a curtain to function as a temporary doorway.\nSince the puja room is compact, the lower ceiling, along with the pyramid-shaped structure offers equilibrium and makes it easier to enter a spiritual experience. The purpose of a threshold is to keep bugs and pests out of sacred areas.\nWhat is the best way to place idols in the temple?\nIt&#8217;s time to put in your idols once your puja room&#8217;s design and construction are complete. A few inches away from the wall and at least six inches from the floor would be preferable. Deceased people&#8217;s portraits and artworks showing violence have no place in your puja room.\nTo maintain consistent air movement around the idol, it should be placed away from the wall. This also helps to surround the deity with the scent of the incense sticks.\nHow should I store things in the puja room?\nAre you unsure about where to put all of your religious literature, candles, and puja items? Storage must always face south-east. Why you may ask? Storage should face south-east to ensure that sunlight is not obstructed. Additionally, there should be no storage above the deity. All storage must be placed under the idols. Disrespect is shown by storing items above idols. It also has an impact on the free movement of energy and light. This is not only helpful in terms of Vastu, but it is also practical because items placed at ground level are easily accessible.\nWhat should be the colour of the puja room?\nThe colour of the prayer room should be according to the Vastu guidelines. Vastu Shastra recommends subdued colours for maintaining the serenity of a puja area. Whites, soft blues, and pastel yellow are all appropriate colours. In a puja room, gloomy colours should be avoided since these will not create a peaceful atmosphere in a place of worship and can be distracting instead. The majority of temple units in Indian houses, however, are constructed of dark wood. This is a Vastu Dosha that prevents divinity from entering your household. If you already have a dark-colored puja unit that you don&#8217;t want to replace, consider painting the wall behind it with a bright colour. To counteract the gloomy colour, the bright colour offers enough illumination to the unit.\nLikewise, for the flooring of your puja area, choose white marble or any light-colored marble tiling.\nWhat should be the lighting of the puja room?\nWhat&#8217;s not to like about a space that&#8217;s bright? And, more importantly, a bright puja room? As it will be the smallest room in your house, it will require bright lighting. With a window facing northeast, light up your prayer area with Diyas. If this isn&#8217;t possible, make do with plenty of artificial lighting.\nNot only will your puja room be bright, but you&#8217;ll also have enough air and be able to sit comfortably while praying for lengthy periods of time if you have a north-east facing window.\nHave a Small Apartment? Here are some tips for the ideal prayer room.\nPeople in today&#8217;s world of nuclear families and small flats don&#8217;t have the luxury of devoting an entire room to praying. The trend for compact fully prepared puja mandaps that can be mounted on walls and hallways has increased as a result.\nLiving Room\nThe greatest spot to install a puja unit in a small flat is in the living room. If you have empty shelves in your entertainment unit, you may create a separate puja room by decorating a tiny section. For those who spend long hours in meditation and prayer, however, solitude and focus will continue to be a problem.\nKitchen\nA kitchen cabinet may be customized to function as a miniature temple. It is advised to make the cabinet door have chiseled edges and shapely openings on its surface so that smoke can be properly dispersed when diyas and fragrance sticks are lighted.\nCorners\nPlacing up a series of elegant pedestals so that the idols are a few inches above the ground level may quickly transform an empty corner of the dining room into a puja space. Small lights can be placed above the idols to brighten the prayer area. If you need seclusion, hang a little curtain beneath the top shelf to keep the idols hidden from view.\nCupboards\nWhy not construct a closet for the deities with sophisticated customizable doors and shelves while constructing a cupboard for everyday use goods at home? This can be the ultimate space-saving puja area for a tiny flat. For further decoration, you can add brass fittings on the cabinet sides and broad shelves with roomy drawers at the bottom.\nDesigning a temple at home: what to do and what not to do\n\nTo maintain the sacredness of the holy place, the puja room should always be separated by doors. As per Vastu, a puja space without a door is inauspicious. This is because the pious spirits inside a puja room might wane if there isn&#8217;t a door.\nA Diya, lamp, or anything else you light in the puja space as per religion must be lit on the right-hand side of the person offering prayers.\nMaintain a clutter-free and spotless puja space.\nEnsure that an electric switchboard is located near the temple so that the area may be lit up during festive occasions.\nWhen worshiping in the puja room, idols and pictures of God must never face each other; deities facing north or east are regarded as auspicious.\nThe shrine should be built high enough for the statues&#8217; feet to be at the level of the chest of the person who is worshiping. Never put the god statue down on the ground.\nA temple or puja area cannot be built against a wall with a bathroom behind it. The justification for not placing the sacred space next to the restroom is to prevent bad energy from entering the house.\nBold or dark hues, such as black, gray, or any other gloomy hue, should never be used in the prayer area.\nAvoid putting trash cans in the puja area since this raises the chances of bad energy flowing through the atmosphere.\nRemove any wilted flowers from the puja space. As soon as the flowers and foliage lose their freshness, remove them from this area.\nIt is deemed inauspicious to place the puja area under a stairway or against the toilet wall. It is considered a big Vastu dosha.\nWhen storing water, make use of copper vessels rather than glass or low-cost metals such as aluminium.\nTo get the greatest benefits, place the puja ghar on the bottom level of your house. According to Vastu, mandirs should not be built in basements or on upper levels.\nAccording to Vastu Shastra, you should not have a temple in your bedroom. If you absolutely have to place it in the bedroom, make sure your feet aren&#8217;t facing the temple.\n\nFAQs\nWhere in the house should the puja area be located?\nBuilding a puja room should be done in the northeast, east, or north orientations. These directions are said to be the luckiest. To guarantee that the puja rooms are free of bad energy, keep them away from the stairwells and restrooms.\nWhich sort of mandir is suitable for use at home?\nA mandir built of wood, as per Vastu Shastra, is auspicious and regarded more holy. Apart from other wood kinds, Sheesham Wood (Rosewood) is deemed blessed for temples.\nWhich metal is considered propitious for puja?\nIt is recommended to utilize objects made of clay, silver, copper, or gold in a puja. Favorable energies are easily received by these things. Owing to the high cost of silver and gold, it may be more cost-effective to use copper, brass, or stone items.\nWhich items should be avoided in the puja room?\nLeather is regarded as an impure material to keep in the mandir. The temple space must not contain any animal skin. Also, don&#8217;t store cash in the puja room. While it is not deemed unclean, saving/storing money at a place where you seek serenity and prosperity is not deemed appropriate.\nWhat Colour scheme should you choose in your puja room? \nChoose pastel colours such as white, blue and yellow. These emit a sense of calm and tranquilly that is conducive to prayer.\nThe post Prayer Room Vastu Shastra Tips For A Peaceful Home appeared first on Real Estate News.",
