            "title": "Opening the Vastu Door to prosperity",
            "content_html": "<p>Vastu is the Indian equivalent of Feng Shui and is a complete guide to getting the best energy out of any house including properties and workplaces. Vastu is an important aspect when it comes to any real estate and today many developers are aware of it and work according to its principles.</p>\n<p>The starting point is the main door of any property which brings energy into the house. The front door is expected to bring good luck, good fortune, and positivity into the house. Certain directions for the main door are good according to Vastu and some directions can lead to Vastu defects. So, we are with some Vastu tips for the main door</p>\n<p>The main objective of Vastu shastra is to integrate architecture with nature.</p>\n<p><strong>The direction of the Main door</strong></p>\n<p>Vastu principles suggest the north, east, northeast, and west are the most favorable directions for the front door. Vastu does not recommend having the main door in the south, southeastern, and northwestern directions. But Vastu has a cure of conditions that cannot be changed and there are ways to compensate for the undesirable directions. One way is to get the front door made in different combinations of wood and metal.</p>\n<p>Vastu shastra recommends setting up different combinations of pyramids and helixes of different inauspicious directions that some front doors open to. Directions of doors in the southwest or southern directions can be compensated by using a lead helix and a lead metal pyramidal combination. An undesirable northwest direction of the main door is recommended for correction by getting the pyramid and helix made of brass. Vastu experts and practitioners recommend the use of a helix made of copper to correct a Vastu defect made led by the door in the southeast direction.</p>\n<p><strong>The best material according to Vastu for the main door</strong></p>\n<p>Among materials used for the main door, the most auspicious one is wood. But if there are Vastu defects of direction, various types of metal combined with wood shall be required for specific direction. For the defect of the south direction, a combination of wood and metal is recommended. Metalwork on the main door is advised if it faces the west. For the favourable directions of east and north, there are some special guidelines. North facing doors can have silver colour doors but for the east, minimal metal on a primarily wooden door works according to Vastu.</p>\n<p><strong>Main door and its visibility as per Vastu</strong></p>\n<p>The main door of any building, house, or establishment is required to be the biggest, ornate and conspicuous. The Main Door is required to open in the clockwise direction and it should be at least 7 feet in height and three feet in width. Vastu shastra recommends that the other doors in the house should be shorter than the height of the main door.</p>\n<p><strong>Vastu and its origins</strong></p>\n<p>The actual name of Vastu shastra is Vastu Shilpa Shastra and it is found in a section of the Atharva Ved which is the Stapatya Ved. It makes Vastu Shashtra, a science that is thousands of years old. The prime essence of Vastu Shastra is the effect of sun rays falling on different areas of a building.\u00a0Vastu shastra was a purely technical subject and was practiced by ancient architects and designers. Evidence of Vastu shastra has been found in the ancient excavated cities of Harappa and Mohenjo Daro. There is a mention of Vastu shastra in the Mahabharat as well as in the Ramayana.</p>\n<p>There is an interesting legend about Lord Shiva overpowering a demon named Andhak after many years of battle. A spirit arose from the perspiration of the Lord and consumed the blood of the demon. The spirit went on to do penance and earned the gratitude of Lord Shiva who offered the spirit a boon. Armed with the boon, the spirit went on to wreak havoc until it was overpowered by 81 Gods led by lord Brahma who had the now repentant spirit face down. Lord Brahma placed a conditional boon to the spirit, saying that those who pray to the spirit as a Vastudevta after building a structure would be blessed and that the spirit was free to torment and trouble those who did not worship it.</p>\n<p>This legend led to the development of Vastu Shastra which has been around since 6000B.C. or even before it. In the early days, Vastu shastra was used mainly in the construction of temples and royal palaces. There is mention of Vastu shastra in the Matsya Puran. The names of the early practitioners of Vastu Shastra reads like a mythological who\u2019s who: Vishwakarma, Narad, Nagnajit, Purandra, Brahma, Bhrigu, Purandara, Nandisa, Adri, Vasista, Sukra, and Brihaspati.\u00a0The first known books on Vastu Shastra were the Kasyapa Silpa and Agama Shastra. The sanctity of Vastu Shastra was such that the ancient architects who were known as sthapatis considered buildings and dwellings as living beings.</p>\n<p><strong>The Science of Vastu Shastra</strong></p>\n<p>It is interesting to know that every building has a horoscope of its own. There are ayadi calculations that attempt to match the horoscope of a building with that of the inhabitants of a house. The horoscope of a building is known as the ayadi shadvarga.</p>\n<p>An important part of Vastu Shastra is known as aya Prakaran where aya denotes income. Aya prakaran needs to be taken up and followed whenever any land is taken up for construction. This will bring good luck and benefits. Some vastu experts can calculate and follow the formulae of Arya and varga. There are nine different vargas.</p>\n<p>8 ayas denote different directions. The Dhwaja aya denotes the east and brings benefits of money. The Dhumra aya of the southeast brings sorrow. The Simha aya of the south denotes luxury. The Svana aya of the southwest has effects of great sins. The gaja aya for the north brings career prospects. The kaka aya of the northeast brings in death.</p>\n<p>Ayas have their hierarchies and are said to have masculine features.</p>\n<p>The Vargas also have different effects. The Swavarga brings monetary benefits, the second is with fewer benefits, the third is auspicious, the fourth has the effect of diseases, the fifth causes enemies, the sixth quarrels/disputes, the seventh with some other benefits and the eighth is the most dangerous with the effects of death.</p>\n<p><strong>Decorating the area around the front door</strong></p>\n<p>The most important aspect for attracting positive energy through the main door is to keep the area around it clean. There should never be a mirror that reflects this door as it will cause the incoming positive energy to bounce back. Also, the main door area needs to be well illuminated.\u00a0Other Vastu tips include having an attractive nameplate with the house number prominently featured on the door.</p>\n<p>Door colour is an important and attractive feature of the main door. Doors should be painted brown, red, pink, and orange if they are facing east. Green and metallic paints are good for main doors facing north. Vastu experts recommend white and light blue for doors facing northeast and southwest direction. Stairs leading to the main door should be of wood or stone and the number of steps should be even.</p>\n<p><strong>Vastu do\u2019s and don\u2019ts for the main door</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Do\u2019s</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Put some good decoration near the main door- The best ones are potted plants.</li>\n<li>Put a nameplate on the front door. If the main door faces the north, use a wooden nameplate.</li>\n<li>Ensure the door opens clockwise and the hinges are well oiled to avoid squeaking.</li>\n<li>Ensure the main door opens to 90 degrees without any obstruction</li>\n<li>Place idols and pictures of Gods and goddesses near the main door.</li>\n<li>Have a foyer or narrow passage from the main door that leads into a wider passage<strong>.\u00a0</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>\u00a0 </strong><strong>Don\u2019ts</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Paint the main door black</li>\n<li>Let the main door face the main door of another house. This will disrupt energy.</li>\n<li>Place shoes or shoe racks near the main door.</li>\n<li>Let the main door stand in a corner.</li>\n<li>Let septic tanks be near the main door.</li>\n<li>Let the shadow of any building nearby fall on the main door</li>\n<li>Keep trash cans or garbage near the main entrance.</li>\n<li>Let the main door face a dilapidated old house that is not occupied</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>What to avoid at the main entrance of the house</strong></p>\n<p>As per Vastu Shastra, the things to avoid at the main entrance of the house are septic tanks, broken furniture, shoes, and shoe racks, sliding or circular opening, temples, and mirrors. The main door should not be at the center of the wall in which it is housed but towards one of the edges. The main entrance should not be in front of intersecting roads.</p>\n<p><strong>Best positions for placing the main door</strong></p>\n<p>The main door should be facing north or east for best results. There are ways to compensate for the Vastu defect caused by the main door facing west and south. If the positioning is inevitable and cannot be changed, there are combinations of pyramids and helixes of different compositions to compensate for the undesirable placements.</p>\n<p>The main door should be positioned towards one of the edges of the wall in which it is placed. If the house is multi-storeyed, the main door on each floor should not be vertically on top and not in the same vertical line.</p>\n<p>The level of the main door is required to be above ground level and it should not face a wall.</p>\n<p><strong>Simple ways to align with Vastu while renovating your house</strong></p>\n<p>Care is to be taken during renovation while painting the main door in colours suited to Vastu. During the renovation, ensure that the main door is not converted into a sliding door or any kind of arched or semi-circular structure.</p>\n<p>Home renovation is a good opportunity to rectify the identified Vastu defects. If a major renovation is being done, the colour, material, decorations around the main door can be rectified. It would be a good idea to consult a Vastu expert for the best advice before the start of renovation so that the best corrections are possible.</p>\n<p>Home renovation should not disrupt the Vastu alignment already in the house. A Vastu expert will give guidance to not only make corrections but also to improve Vastu alignment during the renovation process.</p>\n<p><strong>FAQs</strong><strong>\u00a0</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>\u00a0 \u00a0<strong>Which direction should the entrance of my kitchen face?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>The kitchen should face the east and if not east then the next most auspicious direction is north or west. The kitchen should be in the northwest corner.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>\u00a0 \u00a0<strong>Can I have sliding doors in my main entrance?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>No. Sliding doors are an absolute negation for Vastu. Have a normal manually opening door and do not use automatic door closers.</p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li>\u00a0 \u00a0<strong>Which is the best-recommended place for keeping shoes or shoe racks in the house?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Many houses have shoe racks near the entrance or the main door and this is not recommended in a place from where prosperity is supposed to enter the house. The direction in which shoes are shoe racks is supposed to be kept in the south and southwest direction. If there is no option to keep a shoe rack in any other place other than the main entrance, keep the shoe rack outside the door.</p>\n<ol start=\"4\">\n<li>\u00a0 \u00a0<strong>Is it alright to have my front gate at right angles to the main entrance of my house?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Vastu recommends that the main gate and the main door should both face the same direction. If you have more than one entrance door, select the door facing the gate and make this door the main entrance.</p>\n<ol start=\"5\">\n<li>\u00a0 \u00a0<strong>Can I use a metal door with a wooden casing for my main entrance door?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Vastu shastra recommends a full wooden door with only minimal metal if it is facing the east<strong>.\u00a0</strong>If you still wish to use a metal-reinforced door, the main entrance should face the west.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/opening-the-vastu-door-to-prosperity\">Opening the Vastu Door to prosperity</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog\">Real Estate News</a>.</p>\n",
            "content_text": "Vastu is the Indian equivalent of Feng Shui and is a complete guide to getting the best energy out of any house including properties and workplaces. Vastu is an important aspect when it comes to any real estate and today many developers are aware of it and work according to its principles.\nThe starting point is the main door of any property which brings energy into the house. The front door is expected to bring good luck, good fortune, and positivity into the house. Certain directions for the main door are good according to Vastu and some directions can lead to Vastu defects. So, we are with some Vastu tips for the main door\nThe main objective of Vastu shastra is to integrate architecture with nature.\nThe direction of the Main door\nVastu principles suggest the north, east, northeast, and west are the most favorable directions for the front door. Vastu does not recommend having the main door in the south, southeastern, and northwestern directions. But Vastu has a cure of conditions that cannot be changed and there are ways to compensate for the undesirable directions. One way is to get the front door made in different combinations of wood and metal.\nVastu shastra recommends setting up different combinations of pyramids and helixes of different inauspicious directions that some front doors open to. Directions of doors in the southwest or southern directions can be compensated by using a lead helix and a lead metal pyramidal combination. An undesirable northwest direction of the main door is recommended for correction by getting the pyramid and helix made of brass. Vastu experts and practitioners recommend the use of a helix made of copper to correct a Vastu defect made led by the door in the southeast direction.\nThe best material according to Vastu for the main door\nAmong materials used for the main door, the most auspicious one is wood. But if there are Vastu defects of direction, various types of metal combined with wood shall be required for specific direction. For the defect of the south direction, a combination of wood and metal is recommended. Metalwork on the main door is advised if it faces the west. For the favourable directions of east and north, there are some special guidelines. North facing doors can have silver colour doors but for the east, minimal metal on a primarily wooden door works according to Vastu.\nMain door and its visibility as per Vastu\nThe main door of any building, house, or establishment is required to be the biggest, ornate and conspicuous. The Main Door is required to open in the clockwise direction and it should be at least 7 feet in height and three feet in width. Vastu shastra recommends that the other doors in the house should be shorter than the height of the main door.\nVastu and its origins\nThe actual name of Vastu shastra is Vastu Shilpa Shastra and it is found in a section of the Atharva Ved which is the Stapatya Ved. It makes Vastu Shashtra, a science that is thousands of years old. The prime essence of Vastu Shastra is the effect of sun rays falling on different areas of a building.\u00a0Vastu shastra was a purely technical subject and was practiced by ancient architects and designers. Evidence of Vastu shastra has been found in the ancient excavated cities of Harappa and Mohenjo Daro. There is a mention of Vastu shastra in the Mahabharat as well as in the Ramayana.\nThere is an interesting legend about Lord Shiva overpowering a demon named Andhak after many years of battle. A spirit arose from the perspiration of the Lord and consumed the blood of the demon. The spirit went on to do penance and earned the gratitude of Lord Shiva who offered the spirit a boon. Armed with the boon, the spirit went on to wreak havoc until it was overpowered by 81 Gods led by lord Brahma who had the now repentant spirit face down. Lord Brahma placed a conditional boon to the spirit, saying that those who pray to the spirit as a Vastudevta after building a structure would be blessed and that the spirit was free to torment and trouble those who did not worship it.\nThis legend led to the development of Vastu Shastra which has been around since 6000B.C. or even before it. In the early days, Vastu shastra was used mainly in the construction of temples and royal palaces. There is mention of Vastu shastra in the Matsya Puran. The names of the early practitioners of Vastu Shastra reads like a mythological who\u2019s who: Vishwakarma, Narad, Nagnajit, Purandra, Brahma, Bhrigu, Purandara, Nandisa, Adri, Vasista, Sukra, and Brihaspati.\u00a0The first known books on Vastu Shastra were the Kasyapa Silpa and Agama Shastra. The sanctity of Vastu Shastra was such that the ancient architects who were known as sthapatis considered buildings and dwellings as living beings.\nThe Science of Vastu Shastra\nIt is interesting to know that every building has a horoscope of its own. There are ayadi calculations that attempt to match the horoscope of a building with that of the inhabitants of a house. The horoscope of a building is known as the ayadi shadvarga.\nAn important part of Vastu Shastra is known as aya Prakaran where aya denotes income. Aya prakaran needs to be taken up and followed whenever any land is taken up for construction. This will bring good luck and benefits. Some vastu experts can calculate and follow the formulae of Arya and varga. There are nine different vargas.\n8 ayas denote different directions. The Dhwaja aya denotes the east and brings benefits of money. The Dhumra aya of the southeast brings sorrow. The Simha aya of the south denotes luxury. The Svana aya of the southwest has effects of great sins. The gaja aya for the north brings career prospects. The kaka aya of the northeast brings in death.\nAyas have their hierarchies and are said to have masculine features.\nThe Vargas also have different effects. The Swavarga brings monetary benefits, the second is with fewer benefits, the third is auspicious, the fourth has the effect of diseases, the fifth causes enemies, the sixth quarrels/disputes, the seventh with some other benefits and the eighth is the most dangerous with the effects of death.\nDecorating the area around the front door\nThe most important aspect for attracting positive energy through the main door is to keep the area around it clean. There should never be a mirror that reflects this door as it will cause the incoming positive energy to bounce back. Also, the main door area needs to be well illuminated.\u00a0Other Vastu tips include having an attractive nameplate with the house number prominently featured on the door.\nDoor colour is an important and attractive feature of the main door. Doors should be painted brown, red, pink, and orange if they are facing east. Green and metallic paints are good for main doors facing north. Vastu experts recommend white and light blue for doors facing northeast and southwest direction. Stairs leading to the main door should be of wood or stone and the number of steps should be even.\nVastu do\u2019s and don\u2019ts for the main door\nDo\u2019s\n\nPut some good decoration near the main door- The best ones are potted plants.\nPut a nameplate on the front door. If the main door faces the north, use a wooden nameplate.\nEnsure the door opens clockwise and the hinges are well oiled to avoid squeaking.\nEnsure the main door opens to 90 degrees without any obstruction\nPlace idols and pictures of Gods and goddesses near the main door.\nHave a foyer or narrow passage from the main door that leads into a wider passage.\u00a0\n\n\u00a0 Don\u2019ts\n\nPaint the main door black\nLet the main door face the main door of another house. This will disrupt energy.\nPlace shoes or shoe racks near the main door.\nLet the main door stand in a corner.\nLet septic tanks be near the main door.\nLet the shadow of any building nearby fall on the main door\nKeep trash cans or garbage near the main entrance.\nLet the main door face a dilapidated old house that is not occupied\n\nWhat to avoid at the main entrance of the house\nAs per Vastu Shastra, the things to avoid at the main entrance of the house are septic tanks, broken furniture, shoes, and shoe racks, sliding or circular opening, temples, and mirrors. The main door should not be at the center of the wall in which it is housed but towards one of the edges. The main entrance should not be in front of intersecting roads.\nBest positions for placing the main door\nThe main door should be facing north or east for best results. There are ways to compensate for the Vastu defect caused by the main door facing west and south. If the positioning is inevitable and cannot be changed, there are combinations of pyramids and helixes of different compositions to compensate for the undesirable placements.\nThe main door should be positioned towards one of the edges of the wall in which it is placed. If the house is multi-storeyed, the main door on each floor should not be vertically on top and not in the same vertical line.\nThe level of the main door is required to be above ground level and it should not face a wall.\nSimple ways to align with Vastu while renovating your house\nCare is to be taken during renovation while painting the main door in colours suited to Vastu. During the renovation, ensure that the main door is not converted into a sliding door or any kind of arched or semi-circular structure.\nHome renovation is a good opportunity to rectify the identified Vastu defects. If a major renovation is being done, the colour, material, decorations around the main door can be rectified. It would be a good idea to consult a Vastu expert for the best advice before the start of renovation so that the best corrections are possible.\nHome renovation should not disrupt the Vastu alignment already in the house. A Vastu expert will give guidance to not only make corrections but also to improve Vastu alignment during the renovation process.\nFAQs\u00a0\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0Which direction should the entrance of my kitchen face?\n\nThe kitchen should face the east and if not east then the next most auspicious direction is north or west. The kitchen should be in the northwest corner.\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0Can I have sliding doors in my main entrance?\n\nNo. Sliding doors are an absolute negation for Vastu. Have a normal manually opening door and do not use automatic door closers.\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0Which is the best-recommended place for keeping shoes or shoe racks in the house?\n\nMany houses have shoe racks near the entrance or the main door and this is not recommended in a place from where prosperity is supposed to enter the house. The direction in which shoes are shoe racks is supposed to be kept in the south and southwest direction. If there is no option to keep a shoe rack in any other place other than the main entrance, keep the shoe rack outside the door.\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0Is it alright to have my front gate at right angles to the main entrance of my house?\n\nVastu recommends that the main gate and the main door should both face the same direction. If you have more than one entrance door, select the door facing the gate and make this door the main entrance.\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0Can I use a metal door with a wooden casing for my main entrance door?\n\nVastu shastra recommends a full wooden door with only minimal metal if it is facing the east.\u00a0If you still wish to use a metal-reinforced door, the main entrance should face the west.\nThe post Opening the Vastu Door to prosperity appeared first on Real Estate News.",
